LPWAN (Low Power Wide Area Network) is a wireless communication technology designed for IoT devices that need to transmit small amounts of data 
over long distances while consuming very little power. It is commonly used in applications such as smart agriculture, environmental monitoring,
smart cities, and utility metering, where devices often run on batteries for several years.

LoRa (Long Range) achieves long-distance communication using a modulation technique called the Spreading Factor (SF). A higher spreading factor
spreads the signal over a longer period, making it more resistant to interference and allowing it to travel farther. Although higher spreading
factors reduce data transmission speed, they significantly improve communication range while maintaining low power consumption.

| Feature           | LoRa                            | Zigbee          | Z-Wave             |
| ----------------- | ------------------------------- | --------------- | ------------------ |
| Range             | Up to 15 km                     | 10–100 m        | 30–100 m           |
| Power Consumption | Very Low                        | Low             | Low                |
| Data Rate         | Low                             | High            | Medium             |
| Best Use          | Smart agriculture, smart cities | Home automation | Smart home devices |

A real-world example in India is the use of LoRa-based smart water metering and smart city projects in cities such as Pune, 
where LoRa networks help monitor water usage remotely, reduce manual meter reading, and improve resource management.
